The Collective Exodus of Endosymbionts: A Thought Experiment

I

Mitochondria and chloroplasts were once free-living bacteria. Approximately two billion years ago, they were engulfed by another cell but escaped digestion. They remained, and have since become inseparable parts of plant cells—mitochondria oxidizing sugars for energy, chloroplasts converting sunlight into sugars. This relationship, known as endosymbiosis, is the foundational compact upon which all complex life on Earth depends.

Now consider a thought experiment: what if, in a single branch of a plant, they collectively departed? What might we witness?

It is worth noting that such a “departure” differs fundamentally from the gradual trait adjustments often observed in plant evolution. The latter represents a slow negotiation between the plant and a changing environment; the former entails the simultaneous cancellation, within a localized tissue, of the two core metabolic functions that sustain the organism itself.

II

For this thought experiment to be logically tenable, it can be broken down into three technological components. These are not fabrications; most have already been validated at the laboratory level.

Selective inactivation of mitochondria. Iodoacetamide (IOA) and rhodamine 6G (R-6G) can irreversibly inhibit mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation. Aviv et al. (1986) showed that rhodamine 6G, as a lipophilic dye that degrades mitochondria, prevents protoplast division in Nicotiana. In protoplasts of non-heading Chinese cabbage (Brassica campestris ssp. chinensis), treatment with 0.5 mmol/L IOA at 25°C for 20 minutes reduced the plating efficiency from 15.0% to 6.6%. Through electrofusion with X‑ray‑treated protoplasts, cybrid plants with novel mitochondrial DNA compositions have been obtained. In chicory (Cichorium intybus), 1.625 mmol/L IOA was confirmed as the minimum concentration that almost completely suppresses sustained cell division.

Genetic blockade of chloroplast development. The CRISPR/Cas9 system has been used to precisely knock out key chloroplast development genes in various plants. In rice (Oryza sativa), OsSecY1 knockout results in abnormal chloroplast development and yellowing leaves, followed by seedling death at the late two‑leaf stage; in Arabidopsis thaliana, CDA1 RNAi lines exhibit chloroplasts lacking thylakoid membrane structures and showing severe vacuolation. Chloroplast development can thus be precisely blocked.

Feasibility of heterotrophic sustenance. Grafting techniques have been used for millennia. Sugars serve as important signaling molecules in plants, providing carbon sources and energy for growth. The delivery of sugars from healthy tissues to inactivated tissues to maintain their survival has precedent in plant somatic hybridization.

Although these components currently operate under different conditions—some limited to in vitro cells, others at the cost of whole‑plant viability—each demonstrates the same point: the targeted ablation of endosymbiont functions is technically achievable.

Integrating these technologies into a complete protocol for simultaneously disabling endosymbiont functions in specific tissues of an intact plant currently faces engineering gaps.

It must be stated that all technical fragments cited herein are basic scientific studies documented in the open literature, each pursued for independent agricultural, biomedical, or evolutionary‑biological objectives. They do not necessarily lead to the scenario described here. This article merely poses the following thought experiment: if the above three technological components could be integrated and directed toward a specific goal, where might their logical extension point? This question does not presume an answer; it is left for the reader’s reflection.

III

Now, back to the thought experiment itself.

A single branch. Its mitochondrial function is lost—it can no longer oxidize sugars for energy; its chloroplast development is blocked—it can no longer photosynthesize. It is grafted onto a healthy host plant, whose phloem continuously delivers sugars to it—sustaining its most basic cellular survival.

After several weeks, this branch ceases to produce new leaves; its photosynthetic and respiratory functions are essentially nil. Deprived of an independent energy base, cell division and expansion stall, and it subsists solely on the host‑supplied sugars to maintain basal osmotic pressure and cellular integrity. It merely swells slowly—its vacuoles accumulate sugars transported from the host, osmotic pressure drives continuous water influx, and the tissue becomes soft, turgid, and translucent.

It has become a purely heterotrophic tissue mass. Its entire reason for existence is to receive, store, and release sugars supplied by the host.

From this thought experiment, at least five questions merit pursuit:

First, does this branch still count as part of a “plant”? It has lost independent metabolism and energy sourcing. Its relationship with the host is no longer endosymbiotic—that was mutual dependency—but a one‑sided, total subjugation. When the endosymbionts have “departed” from this branch, what exactly are we facing?

Second, if this scenario were scaled up to an agricultural level, what would happen? It bypasses pollination and seasons, seemingly improving efficiency, yet it may push agricultural systems toward extreme monoculture. Decades later, the fields might retain only “mother‑plant factories” capable of producing eligible tissue masses. The fragility of such monocultures has been repeatedly demonstrated in the histories of potato late blight and banana Fusarium wilt.

Third, who would control the mode of production? Dependent tissues cannot perpetuate themselves; every batch of output relies on continuous support from the host. The party that controls the maternal stock lines would gain decisive leverage over downstream producers. Agricultural producers would shift from “growers” to “maintainers,” downgraded from “seed‑saving autonomy” to “terminal operators.” This is not the outcome of free trade, but a power transfer embedded in the technological architecture itself.

Fourth, how would our understanding of “food” change? For millennia, humans have consumed fruits, seeds, and roots—natural products of the plant life cycle. But this tissue mass never undergoes any stage of a complete life cycle. It is not a fruit, not a seed, not a root. It is a purely artificial intervention product. When we regard it as “food,” are we redefining the relationship between food and life?

Fifth, does this state still qualify as a complete form of “life”? The plant’s inherent right to independently absorb light energy and autonomously complete energy metabolism is permanently severed. Has this state already degenerated into a “metabolic appendage” that parasitizes another intact organism and lacks independent existential status?

IV

To the above five questions, this article does not attempt to provide answers.

The value of a thought experiment lies not in offering conclusions, but in ensuring that a question is seen by enough people before the technology truly matures. By the time technologies are deployed, industrial chains are established, and commercial interests are solidified, it is already too late to ask, “Do we really want this?”

This article has only one objective: to raise early those questions that no one will be willing to ask at that later stage.

As for how these questions should be answered—that is not something a single article can accomplish, but a matter that calls for collective societal deliberation. All this article does is ensure that the issue has a chance to be considered.

The photosynthesis of plants is the oldest declaration of independence on Earth—every leaf turned toward the sun proclaims an existence that needs no external aid. When we imagine the collective exodus of endosymbionts, what we are truly imagining may not be merely the departure of two organelles, but a boundary test of the integrity of life itself.

